<POSTER> richard kennedy </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2003-09-09T15:28:00 </POSTDATE>

In August of 2001 Robert Brazil posted this listing below to the
Phaeton group. What's to be noticed is that the stoney broke and
buggering Edward de Vere was admired for some reason or other, and one
wonders what it was. Notice also that several of the books are of a
religious nature, which freshens the notion that he might have had
something to do with &quot;translating&quot; the KJV.

---------------------------------

(clip of Brazil's intro.)

Brazil's Lists of the Printed Dedications to Edward de Vere and
related Books
version 3.0 / c. 2001

Books dedicated exclusively and overtly to the 17th Earl of Oxford

1. Hist. of Trogus Pompeius Arthur Golding 1564

2. An Aethiopian History Thomas Underdowne 1569

3. Peisistratus and Catanea Edmund Elviden c1570

4. Psalms of David Arthur Golding 1571

5. Cardanus Comfort Thomas Bedingfeld 1573

6. The Breviary of Britain Thomas Twyne 1573

7. Oleum Magistrale George Baker 1574

8. The Staff of Christian Faith John Brooke 1577

9. The Mirror of Mutability Anthony Munday 1579

10. Defense of the Military... Geffrey Gates 1579

11. Zelauto Anthony Munday 1580

12. Euphues and his England John Lyly 1580

13. Phiravanti ... on Surgery John Hester 1580

14. Diverse Sermons of Calvin Thomas Stocker 1581

15. Hekatompathia Thomas Watson 1582

16. Pandora John Southern 1584

17. Carde of Fancie Robert Greene 1584

18. The English Secretary Angel Daye 1586

19. Palmerin d'Oliva part 1 Anthony Munday 1588

21. Plainsong Diverse &amp; sundry John Farmer 1591

22. English Madrigals John Farmer 1599

23. English Secretary Revised Angel Daye 1599

24. Pract. of New &amp; Old Physic George Baker 1599

Multiple Dedicatees, including EO:

25. Gratulationes Val ... Book 4 Gabriel Harvey 1578
26. Faerie Queene Spenser 1590
27. Ecclesiastes Henry Lok 1597
28. Anagrammata F.D. 1603

Debatable:

Euphues Anatomy of Wit 1617 John Lyly Reprint 1617
Palmerin d'Oliva part 2 Anthony Munday Reprint of1615

Covert:

Strange Newes Thomas Nashe 1592
Minerva Britanna Peacham 1612
etc.

OXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXXO

Dedicated to Anne Cecil de Vere, the Countess Oxford:

1.The new Jewel of Health George Baker 1576

2. Epistle of St. Paul to Ephesians N. Hemming 1581

3. A Christian Discourse .. John Brooke 1578

4. Golden Epistles Geoffrey Fenton

5. St. John Chrysotom exposition upon the Epistle ...

OXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXXOXOXO

Dedicated to Henry the 18th EO:

* The nine English Worthies Robert Fletcher 1606 multiple deds.

* Hiren : or the faire Greek William Barksted 1611

* A funerall poem ... Sir Francis Vere Cyril Tourener 1611

* Primaleon of Greece Anthony Munday 1619

* Treatise on Hawks and hunting Edmond Bert 1619

* Honour in his perfection ... Gervase Markham 1624

* The booke of Honor Francis Markham 1625

* Teares of Heraclitus A Darcie multiple

OXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXOXO

Notes:

Franklin Williams' list suggests that the Euphues Anatomy of Wit
reprint of 1617 is dedicated to Oxford, though the original isn't. I
haven't seen the 1617 yet.

In the covert department there are probably many examples beyond
Nashe's
Strange Newes.

One of the most interesting dedications is Angel Daye's The English
Secretary of 1586 which begins:

&quot; Zeuxis endeavoring to paint excellent lie, made grapes in shew so
natural that presenting them to view, men were deceived by their
shapes and the birds with their colors. When Apelles drew Venus ... &quot;
Daye then goes on to flatter Oxford as being in the same category
of talent as Zeuxis and Apelles.

To me, the &quot;killer&quot; aspect of the Oxford dedications books is that so
many are on the list of Bullough's Sources of Shakespeare. And others
probably should be on the list as well.

The &quot;Dedicated to Oxford&quot; books are important because they provide
research vectors - through the texts, through the bibliographic
details, and through the authors and alleged authors of the
works.investigating the authors of the
books, many of whom are cited by Stratfordians as authors of works
used by Shakespeare.

The broader issue to be determined is whether any generalizations can
be formed about what it meant to have a book dedication in those days,
whether contact &amp; friendship between author and recipient can be
reliably inferred, or if patterns of social &amp; 'business' connections
can be reconstructed. An additional issue is: when is a book
dedication a plea for money, and when does it represent pre-paid
patronage ?

Another prickly issue is the spectre of &quot;phony name&quot; authors who might
represent the patron ghosting his own book and dedication (as has been
suggested in the case of Robert Greene's dedication to Oxford in &quot;
Card of Fancie&quot;).

Print shops 400 years ago shared one thing with modern times: up front
cash money to begin the press run. The exception to this rule is when
the printer or publisher (often in an alliance) owned the project or
an interest in it.

What I am trying to determine over time is whether it can be proven
that major patrons of books, like Leicester, Burghley, and Oxford,
took an active interest in some of those books that bear their names,
and that their interest included not just the outlaying of money, but
occasionally some editorial or &quot;publisher&quot; functions. In Oxford's
case, it is seems almost intuitively obvious that de Vere took an
active role in &quot;producing&quot; some of the books, even if that took the
form of delegating the jobs to others and then carefully examining the
results and approving or nixing. &quot;Proving&quot; that involvement is not
going to be easy, but it's a fine challenge.

Robert Brazil

The best sources for beginning an investigation into this is:

Franklin B. Williams: Index of dedications ... 1962
K. Chiljan : Dedication Letters to the Earl of Oxford 1994

