The KJV of the Bible presents the same problem as the Shakespeare
Authorship. Although it is certain that King James authorized the
Bible, which was to correct and amend existing versions, and that he
appointed a group of scholars, 56?, to work on it, after that it gets
mysterious. Each group was assigned different portions of the Bible,
yet there is no evidence of any communication between the scholars,
notes, places of meetings or anything else about the group's
activities. As with the man from Stratford, assumptions are made that
this group wrote it, and then the case made by words such as &quot;must be
the case,&quot;&quot;most assuredly,&quot;&quot;without a doubt,&quot; etc.

The second problem with the KJV is that there is a unity of style to
the entire work as if it had been written by one man. More than one
man has suggested that the two greatest works of the English language
are the KJV and Shakespeare's works. The parallels and knowledge of
the Bible by the author Shakespeare are also quite extraordinary.

Oxfordians are caught in their paradigm of believing that Oxford died
in 1604, although the evidence on that is quite conjectural. While
Oxfordians make the case that the man from Stratford could not be the
author, one of the reasons being that he was not eulogized at his
death, strangely they fall silent as to why there were no public
eulogies of Oxford (Shakespeare or not), burial ceremony or other
public displays concerning his death. He was on good terms with James
I, so why not? Also, there are articles written in SF by a doctor
that say the plague is not the cause of Oxford's death.

Oxford, of course, had a well marked Geneva Bible, and even if not
Shakespeare, his knowledge of the Bible was rather extensive.

To say that Oxford, or whomever, wrote the KJV is not exactly correct.
Rather, it was a combination of editing, rewriting, cleaning up, etc.,
to give it a new unity and freshness. For example, changing passive to
active tense, etc.

However, whoever worked on the Bible seemed to work mostly from the
Geneva Bible, and overlooked the Coverdale Bible, which in some cases
has more poetic merit than the KJV. Remember that strict
interpretation of the original Hebrew was not issue. Here is the
Cloverdale vs. KJV

Job 14:1, 2
Coverdale
Man that is born of a woman hath but a short time to live and is full
of diverse miseries.
He cometh up and falleth away like a flower

KJV
Man that is born of a woman is of few days, and full of trouble.
He cometh forth like a flower, and is cut down.

There is a poetic-literary choice made here. My preference is that the
flower blooms and then falls away, while the KJV chooses to say that
the flower comes forth and then is violently cut down, which is not at
all the sense of the Coverdale, and would seem less appropriate to
flowers. Oh, well, simply a matter of taste.

Here is another set of differences between the Coverdale, Geneva and
KJV.

There is even a loss of meaning from the Coverdale to the Geneva not
corrected in the KJV. Here the man is excused from military duty so
that he may sleep with his wife, and presumably have children. The
sense of this is lost by the KJV. The sense of sexuality and
procreation are lost by the time one gets to the KJV.

Deuteronomy 24:5
Coverdale
When a man hath newly taken a wife, he shall not go out a warfare,
neither shall he be charged with withal. He shall be free in his house
one year long, that he may be merry with his wife which he hath taken.

Geneva
When a man taketh a new wife, he shall not go a warfare, neither shall
he be charged with any business, but shall be free at home one year,
and rejoice with his wife which he hath taken.

KJV
When a man hath taken a new wife, he shall not go out to war, neither
shall he be charged with any business; but he shall be free at home
one year, and shall cheer up his wife which he hath taken.

The unity of the KJV and the deliberate artistic choices, and a unity
of those choices, indicate that one man was most likely responsible
for the editing of the KJV. Again, a theory much advanced, just there
seem to be no likely candidates around to do the job. Of course,
there is Oxford, but since he died, hardly seems like the case, or did
he not die, but just disappear?

Paul Streitz

