Notes:

Franklin Williams' list suggests that the Euphues Anatomy of Wit
reprint of 1617 is dedicated to Oxford, though the original isn't. I
haven't seen the 1617 yet.

In the covert department there are probably many examples beyond
Nashe's
Strange Newes.

One of the most interesting dedications is Angel Daye's The English
Secretary of 1586 which begins:

&quot; Zeuxis endeavoring to paint excellent lie, made grapes in shew so
natural that presenting them to view, men were deceived by their
shapes and the birds with their colors. When Apelles drew Venus ... &quot;
Daye then goes on to flatter Oxford as being in the same category
of talent as Zeuxis and Apelles.

To me, the &quot;killer&quot; aspect of the Oxford dedications books is that so
many are on the list of Bullough's Sources of Shakespeare. And others
probably should be on the list as well.

The &quot;Dedicated to Oxford&quot; books are important because they provide
research vectors - through the texts, through the bibliographic
details, and through the authors and alleged authors of the
works.investigating the authors of the
books, many of whom are cited by Stratfordians as authors of works
used by Shakespeare.

The broader issue to be determined is whether any generalizations can
be formed about what it meant to have a book dedication in those days,
whether contact &amp; friendship between author and recipient can be
reliably inferred, or if patterns of social &amp; 'business' connections
can be reconstructed. An additional issue is: when is a book
dedication a plea for money, and when does it represent pre-paid
patronage ?

Another prickly issue is the spectre of &quot;phony name&quot; authors who might
represent the patron ghosting his own book and dedication (as has been
suggested in the case of Robert Greene's dedication to Oxford in &quot;
Card of Fancie&quot;).

Print shops 400 years ago shared one thing with modern times: up front
cash money to begin the press run. The exception to this rule is when
the printer or publisher (often in an alliance) owned the project or
an interest in it.

What I am trying to determine over time is whether it can be proven
that major patrons of books, like Leicester, Burghley, and Oxford,
took an active interest in some of those books that bear their names,
and that their interest included not just the outlaying of money, but
occasionally some editorial or &quot;publisher&quot; functions. In Oxford's
case, it is seems almost intuitively obvious that de Vere took an
active role in &quot;producing&quot; some of the books, even if that took the
form of delegating the jobs to others and then carefully examining the
results and approving or nixing. &quot;Proving&quot; that involvement is not
going to be easy, but it's a fine challenge.

Robert Brazil

The best sources for beginning an investigation into this is:

Franklin B. Williams: Index of dedications ... 1962
K. Chiljan : Dedication Letters to the Earl of Oxford 1994
