"/>

However sane Dooley and Price may be, they are not Oxfordians; Price used
to be an Oxfordian, and her writings are marred by (among other things) a
clinging to some of the weakest views of some of the least reliable of
Oxfordians; she is perhaps best described as &quot;recovering&quot; but subject to
relapse.

Some Oxfordians in the SF do seem to be fond of the &quot;Prince Tudor&quot; bit,
but it is hardly definitive of the organization. I don't know anybody in
the SF that I would consider insane -- or even more likely to be &quot;wacky&quot;
than antistratfordians outside the SF.

There are antistratfordians of various stripes who are demonstrably
capable of acute insights and even careful research when the topic at hand
does not draw too near their own particular brand of folly. The &quot;Prince
Tudor&quot; bit, as silly as it is, is not much sillier than the &quot;Oxford wrote
almost everything&quot; view promulgated by a number of non-PT Oxfordians.

Joseph Sobran, who I don't believe is a member of the SF, and who does not
seem to accept the PT theory, might be thought one of the &quot;saner&quot;
Oxfordians, but this presumably saner person thinks not only that Oxford
wrote his own poems AND Shakespeare's works but that he also wrote the
sonnets of Sidney, Daniel, Spenser, Daniel, Drayton -- in fact, just about
all the Elizabethan sonnets that we have. See Sobran's essay &quot;The Bard's
Orphans&quot; at

Sobran opens his essay with the words &quot;Maybe I'm crazy.&quot; The editor of
his website ASKED me to put a link to this essay on the Shakespeare
Authorship page, and I of course obliged.

If there is a line separating &quot;saner&quot; Oxfordians from &quot;wack-jobs,&quot; it
cannot reasonably be drawn in such a way as to put the non-PT and non-SF
Sobran in the &quot;saner&quot; camp and the SF in the other. Unlike Sobran, the SF
has also made at least one genuine contribution to the record in
publishing Paul Altrocchi's essay on the annnotation in which Shakespeare
is described as &quot;our Roscius.&quot;

