Dr. Paul Altrocchi wrote a rather interesting and cogent article in
Shakespeare Matters (&quot;It was not Ye Plague&quot;) which indicated that
although many Oxfordians have believed for some time that Oxford died
of the plague, there is no evidence to suppose that he did. There were
no cases of plague in Hackney in July of 1604. The last &quot;sporadic&quot;
recorded case was in June. Altrocchi conducted more research and also
examined the death records. There was no diagnosis of &quot;Ye Plague&quot; next
to the entry for Edward de Vere.

I am a little more skeptical. It's well known that the rich could
&quot;bargain&quot; the plague tag away so they didn't have to observe
quarantine. But you are arguing *with* Altrocchi, David--although his
forum is, according to you, &quot;about on a par with that of the Weekly
World News&quot;--not against him, as he too believes the cause of Oxford's
death is unknown. Although he leans towards a diagnosis of Myocardial
Infarction (I believe Altrocchi is a cardiologist), and gives reasons
for his theory, the last sentence of the article reads: &quot;There is
insufficient evidence to allow a conclusive diagnosis of De Vere's
death at the age of 54.&quot;

